'''[[Children in the military]]''' are children (defined by the [[Convention on the Rights of the Child]] as persons under the age of 18) who are associated with military organizations, such as state [[Military|armed forces]] and [[Violent non-state actor|non-state armed groups]].<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://www.unicef.org/emerg/files/ParisPrinciples310107English.pdf|title=The Paris Principles: Principles and guidelines on children associated with armed forces or armed groups|last=UNICEF|first=|date=2007|website=|access-date=2018-01-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030083755/http://www.unicef.org/emerg/files/ParisPrinciples310107English.pdf|archive-date=30 October 2016|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Throughout history and in many cultures, children have been involved in military campaigns.<ref name="Wessells">{{cite journal|last1=Wessels|first1=Michael|title=Child Soldiers|journal=Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists|date=1997|volume=53|issue=4|page=32}}</ref> For example, thousands of children participated on all sides of the First World War and the Second World War.<ref name=":41">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/guides/zcvdhyc |title=How did Britain let 250000 underage soldiers fight in WW1? |work=BBC News |access-date=23 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321184716/http://www.bbc.co.uk/guides/zcvdhyc |archive-date=21 March 2018 |dead-url=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=":43">[[Norman Davies]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=Jzxt9FFBDPwC&pg=PA603 ''Rising '44: The Battle for Warsaw,''] Pan Books 2004 p.603</ref><ref name="Rosen2005">{{cite book |author=David M. Rosen |title=Armies of the Young: Child Soldiers in War and Terrorism |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zQYQ0tho6mAC&pg=PA55 |date=January 2005 |publisher=Rutgers University Press |isbn=978-0-8135-3568-5 |pages=54–55 |quote=The participation of Jewish children and youth in warfare was driven by a combination of necessity, honor, and moral duty.}}</ref><ref name="Kucherenko2011">{{cite book |last=Kucherenko |first=Olga |title=Little Soldiers: How Soviet Children Went to War, 1941–1945 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=92R8Pmr6xoAC&pg=PR3-IA96 |date=13 January 2011 |publisher=OUP Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-161099-8 |page=3}}</ref> Children may be trained and used for combat, assigned to support roles such as porters or messengers, or used for tactical advantage as [[human shield]]s or for political advantage in [[propaganda]].<ref name=":2" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.historyextra.com/podcast/children-war|title=Children at war|work=History Extra|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180112002342/http://www.historyextra.com/podcast/children-war|archive-date=12 January 2018|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

Children are easy targets for [[military recruitment]] due to their greater susceptibility to influence compared to adults.<ref name="Wessells" /><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Beber, Blattman|first1=Bernd, Christopher|title=The Logic of Child Soldiering and Coercion|journal=International Organization|date=2013|volume=67|issue=1|pages=65–104|doi=10.1017/s0020818312000409}}</ref><ref name=":32">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/427757599|title=On killing : the psychological cost of learning to kill in war and society|last=Dave.|first=Grossman,|date=2009|publisher=Little, Brown and Co|isbn=9780316040938|edition=Rev.|location=New York|oclc=427757599}}</ref><ref name=":22">{{Cite book|chapter=Joining the ranks: The role of indoctrination in transforming civilians to service members|author1=McGurk, Dennis|author2=Cotting, Dave I.|author3=Britt, Thomas W.|author4=Adler, Amy B.|title=Military life: The psychology of serving in peace and combat|volume= Volume 2: Operational stress|editor1=Adler, Amy B.|editor2=Castro, Carl Andrew|editor3=Britt, Thomas W.|publisher=Praeger Security International|year=2006|isbn=978-0275983024|location=Westport|pages=13–31}}</ref> Some children are recruited by force while others choose to join up, often to escape poverty or because they expect military life to offer a [[rite of passage]] to maturity.<ref name="Wessells" />

{{Further|Children in the military}}

==Pre-20th century==
{{Refimprove section|date=May 2018}}
[[File:NinoHeroe.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Mexico honors [[Niños Héroes|its cadets]] who died in the Battle of Chapultepec (1847).]]
[[File:UnionPowderMonkey.jpg|thumb|upright|left|A [[powder monkey]] on a Union vessel, American Civil War.]]

Throughout history and in many cultures, children have been extensively involved in military campaigns.<ref name="Wessells" />

The earliest mentions of minors being involved in wars come from antiquity. It was customary for youths in the Mediterranean basin to serve as aides, charioteers and armor bearers to adult warriors. Examples of this practice can be found in the Bible, such as David's service to King Saul, in Hittite and ancient Egyptian art, and in ancient Greek [[Greek mythology|mythology]] (such as the story of Hercules and Hylas), philosophy and literature.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} In a practice dating back to antiquity, children were routinely taken on a campaign, together with the rest of a military man's family, as part of the baggage.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}

The Roman Empire made use of youths in war, though it was understood that it was unwise and cruel to use children in war, and Plutarch implies that regulations required youths to be at least sixteen years of age.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} Despite this, several Roman [[Legionary|legionaries]] were known to have enlisted aged 14 in the [[Imperial Roman army]], such as Quintus Postunius Solus who completed 21 years of service in [[Legio XX Valeria Victrix]], and Caecilius Donatus who served 26 years in the Legio XX and died shortly before his honorable discharge.<ref>{{cite book|last=Cowan |first=Ross |authorlink=Ross Cowan |ref=harv |title=Roman Legionary AD 69–161 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QKudCwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=de#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=2013 |publisher=[[Osprey Publishing]] |location=[[Oxford]] |isbn=978-1780965871 |page=12 }}</ref>

In medieval Europe young boys from about twelve years of age were used as military aides ("[[squires]]"), though in theory their role in actual combat was limited. The so-called [[Children's Crusade]] in 1212 recruited thousands of children as untrained soldiers under the assumption that divine power would enable them to conquer the enemy, although none of the children entered combat. According to the legend, they were instead sold into slavery. While most scholars no longer believe that the Children's Crusade consisted solely, or even mostly, of children, it nonetheless exemplifies an era in which entire families took part in a war effort.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}

Young boys often took part in battles during early modern warfare. When Napoleon was faced with invasion by a massive Allied force in 1814 he conscripted many teenagers for his armies. Orphans of the Imperial Guard fought in the Netherlands with Marshal MacDonald and were between the ages of 14 and 17.<ref>Michael Leggiere, The Fall of Napoleon: The Allied Invasion of France 1813–1814, pg.99–100</ref> Many of the conscripts who reported to the ranks in 1814 were referred to as Marie Louises after the Empress Marie Louise of France; they were also known as "The Infants of the Emperor". These soldiers were in their mid-teens.<ref>Stephen Pope, Dictionary of the Napoleonic Wars, p. 318</ref> One of their more visible roles was as the ubiquitous "[[Drummer boy (military)|drummer boy]]".

During the age of sail, young boys formed part of the crew of British Royal Navy ships and were responsible for many essential tasks including bringing powder and shot from the [[Magazine (artillery)#Naval magazines|ship's magazine]] to the gun crews. These children were called "powder monkeys."{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}

[[File:Child soldier in the US Civil War.jpg|thumb|upright|Drummer boy [[John Clem]] during the American Civil War.]]

During the American Civil War a young boy, Bugler John Cook, served in the US Army at the age of 15 and received the Medal of Honor for his acts during the Battle of Antietam, the bloodiest day in American history.<ref>Slinger, P. W. Children at War. New York: Pantheon Books, 2005.</ref> Several other minors, including 11-year-old [[Willie Johnston (Medal of Honor recipient)|Willie Johnston]], have also received the Medal of Honor.<ref>{{cite web |author=Lewis D. Eigen |title=Unfortunately Child Soldiers are Nothing New |publisher=Scriptamus.wordpress.com |year=2009 |url=http://scriptamus.wordpress.com/2009/11/02/child-soldiers-are-unfortunately-nothing-new/ |access-date=23 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323201709/https://scriptamus.wordpress.com/2009/11/02/child-soldiers-are-unfortunately-nothing-new/ |archive-date=23 March 2018 |dead-url=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

By a law signed by Nicholas I of Russia in 1827 a disproportionate number of Jewish boys, known as the [[cantonist]]s, were forced into military training establishments to serve in the army. The 25-year conscription term officially commenced at the age of 18, but boys as young as eight were routinely taken to fulfill the quota. {{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}

In the final stages of the Paraguayan War, children fought in the Battle of Acosta Ñu against the Allied forces of Brazil, Argentina and Uruguay. The day is commemorated as a national holiday in Paraguay.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}

During the Boshin War, the pro-''shōgun'' Aizu Domain formed the {{nihongo|''[[Byakkotai]]''|白虎隊|extra="[[White Tiger (Chinese constellation)|White Tiger]] Force"}}, which was made up of the 16 to 17-year-old sons of Aizu samurai. During the Battle of Bonari Pass and the Battle of Aizu they fought the Satcho forces who supported the Imperial cause. A detached unit of Byakkotai was cut off from the rest of the unit and retreated to Iimori Hill, which overlooked Aizu-Wakamatsu Castle. From there, they saw what they thought was the castle on fire. 20 of the detached unit committed ''seppuku'' while [[Iinuma Sadakichi|one was unsuccessful]]. He was saved by a local peasant.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}

==World War I==
[[File:Momčilo Gavrić i major Stevan Tucović.jpg|thumb|Momčilo Gavrić and another soldier reporting to major Stevan Tucović, 1916.]]

The youngest known soldier of World War I was [[Momčilo Gavrić (soldier)|Momčilo Gavrić]], who joined the 6th Artillery Division of the Serbian Army at the age of 8, after Austro-Hungarian troops in August 1914 killed his parents, grandmother, and seven of his siblings.<ref name="novosti">[http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/naslovna/drustvo/aktuelno.290.html:451827-Momcilo-Gavric---najmladji-vojnik-Prvog-svetskog-rata Momčilo Gavrić – najmlađi vojnik Prvog svetskog rata] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326180109/http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/naslovna/drustvo/aktuelno.290.html:451827-Momcilo-Gavric---najmladji-vojnik-Prvog-svetskog-rata |date=26 March 2018 }} ("Večernje novosti", 31 August 2013)</ref><ref name=AuntieMabel>{{cite book|last1=Wenzel|first1=Marian|last2=Cornish|first2=John|title=Auntie Mabel's war: an account of her part in the hostilities of 1914–18|year=1980|publisher=Allen Lane|page=112}}</ref><ref name=BiografskiRecnik>{{cite book|title=Srpski biografski rečnik, vol II|year=2004|publisher=Budućnost|page=601}}</ref>

In the West, boys [[Youngest British soldier in World War I|as young as 12]] were caught up in the overwhelming tide of patriotism and in huge numbers enlisted for active service. Others enlisted to avoid harsh and dreary lives. Typically many were able to pass themselves off as older men, such as George Thomas Paget, who at 17 joined a [[Bantam (military)|Bantam]] battalion in the Welsh Regiment. The last surviving combat veteran of the War was [[Claude Choules]], who enlisted in the [[Royal Navy]] at age 14 and saw his first action at the Battle of Jutland at 15.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} In the Gallipoli campaign, otherwise known as "Çanakkale", children as young as 15 fought in the trenches. 120 children fought in the "15'liler" or "The 15s" company, with no known survivors.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}

==Spanish Civil War==
Many child soldiers fought in the Spanish Civil War:
{{quote|The centuria was an untrained mob composed mostly of boys in their teens. Here and there in the militia you came across children as young as eleven or twelve, usually refugees from Fascist territory who had been enlisted as militiamen as the easiest way of providing for them. As a rule, they were employed on light work in the rear, but sometimes they managed to worm their way to the front line, where they were a public menace. I remember one little brute throwing a hand-grenade into the dug-out fire 'for a joke'. At Monte Pocero I do not think there was anyone younger than fifteen, but the average age must have been well under twenty. Boys of this age ought never to be used in the front line, because they cannot stand the lack of sleep which is inseparable from trench warfare. At the beginning it was almost impossible to keep our position properly guarded at night. The wretched children of my section could only be roused by dragging them out of their dug-outs feet foremost, and as soon as your back was turned they left their posts and slipped into shelter; or they would even, in spite of the frightful cold, lean up against the wall of the trench and fall fast asleep.|||George Orwell<ref>{{cite web|first=George |last=Orwell |title=Homage to Catalonia {{!}} Chapter 3 |url=http://www.george-orwell.org/Homage_to_Catalonia/2.html |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318152354/http://www.george-orwell.org/Homage_to_Catalonia/2.html |archivedate=18 March 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>}}

==World War II==
[[File:Warsaw Uprising - Young Soldiers (1944).jpg|thumb|upright|Child soldiers during the Warsaw Uprising]]

{{main|Military use of children in World War II}}

In [[World War II]] children under the age of 18 were widely used by all sides in formal and informal military roles. Children were readily indoctrinated into the prevailing ideology of the warring parties, quickly trained, and often sent to the front line; many were wounded or killed. The lack of a legal definition of a child, combined with the absence of a system for verifying the ages of prospective child recruits, contributed to the extensive use of children in the war.

==After World War II: Historical examples by region==
These are historical examples. For instances of children in the military today, see [[Children in the military]].

=== Africa ===

==== Algeria ====
During the [[Algerian Civil War|Algerian civil war]] (1991–2002) children were recruited frequently by [[Islamism|Islamist]] armed groups fighting the government.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/Handlers/Download.ashx?IDMF=adc88bff-1916-4317-b184-d9079e7b0bb8|title=Global Report on Child Soldiers|last=Coalition to Stop the Use of Child Soldiers|first=|date=2001|website=child-soldiers.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> A government-allied militia—the Legitimate Defence Groups (LDG)—also used children, according to some reports.<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":6">{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/Handlers/Download.ashx?IDMF=c5f157d3-4b56-457c-a2d8-31601ffc1b9e|title=Child Soldiers Global Report 2004|last=Coalition to Stop the Use of Child Soldiers|first=|date=2004|website=child-soldiers.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> Although the rules for joining the LDG were the same as the army, in which only adults were recruited (by [[conscription]]) the LDG applied no safeguards to ensure that children could not join up.<ref name=":6" /> The extent of child recruitment during the war remains unknown.<ref name=":6" />

==== Burundi ====
Children were kidnapped and used extensively during the civil war of 1993–2005.<ref name=":37">{{Cite book|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/Handlers/Download.ashx?IDMF=26c0549d-aa35-4f1a-8e34-5956f8e2ec51|title=Child Soldiers Global Report 2008 (Burundi)|last=Coalition to Stop the Use of Child Soldiers (now Child Soldiers International)|first=|publisher=|year=2008|isbn=|location=London|pages=77–81}}</ref> In 2004 hundreds of child soldiers were in the [[Party for the Liberation of the Hutu People|Forces Nationales pour la Libération]] (FNL), an armed rebel, Hutu group.<ref name="CSUCS-13">[https://web.archive.org/web/20091226221427/http://www.child-soldiers.org/document/get?id=743 Child soldiers global report 2004: Africa Regional overview], [http://www.child-soldiers.org/contact/contact Child Soldiers International] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20070703045854/http://www.child-soldiers.org/contact/contact|date=3 July 2007}}.<!--Retrieved April 2009--></ref> Children between the ages of 10 and 16 were also conscripted by the Burundese military.<ref name="CSUCS-13" />

After the Arusha peace accord of 2001 and the Pretoria agreement of 2003 eventually brought the conflict to an end in 2005,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://africacenter.org/spotlight/burundi-why-the-arusha-accords-are-central/|title=Burundi: Why the Arusha Accords are Central|last=Nantulya|first=P|date=2015-08-05|work=Africa Center for Strategic Studies|access-date=2018-02-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321133507/http://africacenter.org/spotlight/burundi-why-the-arusha-accords-are-central/|archive-date=21 March 2018|dead-url=no|language=en-US|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the new constitution committed to not using children in direct combat.<ref name=":37" /> The parties to the conflict no longer recruited children in large numbers, but many remained active in the FNL, which had denounced the peace accord.<ref name=":37" />

By 2006, a [[Disarmament, demobilization, and reintegration|reintegration program]] organized by [[UNICEF]] had led to the release of 3,000 children from the military and armed groups.<ref name=":37" /> According to Child Soldiers International:<blockquote>The majority of those [children] who took part in the program returned to farm and fish in their local communities, but nearly 600 returned to school. Some 1,800 former child soldiers received occupational training. Health care was provided for those with special needs and [[Psychosocial|psychosocial support]] was provided through individual and group meetings.<ref name=":37" /></blockquote>{{As of|2017}}, Burundi no longer appears on the UN list of countries where children are used in hostilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.un.org/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=S/2017/821&Lang=E&Area=UNDOC|title=Children and Armed Conflict: Report of the Secretary-General, 2017|last=UN General Assembly|first=|date=2017|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180125015450/http://www.un.org/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=S%2F2017%2F821&Lang=E&Area=UNDOC|archive-date=25 January 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=2018-05-21|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

==== Chad ====
Between 2007 and 2012, children were used extensively by the Chadian military as participants in armed conflict.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://childsoldiersworldindex.org/view/TD|title=Child Soldiers World Index: Chad|last=Child Soldiers International|first=|date=2018|website=childsoldiersworldindex.org|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330013128/http://childsoldiersworldindex.org/view/TD|archive-date=30 March 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=2018-03-29|df=dmy-all}}</ref> They were also integrated into various rebel forces, including the [[United Front for Democratic Change]] (''Front Uni pour le Changement'', FUC), local self-defense forces known as ''Tora Boro'' militias, and two Sudanese rebel movements operating in Chad: the [[Justice and Equality Movement]] (JEM) and the G-19 faction of the Sudanese Liberation Army (SLA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hrw.org/reports/2007/chad0107/|title=They Came Here to Kill Us|date=January 2007|publisher=Human Rights Watch|access-date=29 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328114459/https://www.hrw.org/reports/2007/chad0107//|archive-date=28 March 2017|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hrw.org/reports/2007/chad0707/|title=Early To War|date=July 2007|publisher=Human Rights Watch|access-date=29 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016121224/https://www.hrw.org/reports/2007/chad0707/|archive-date=16 October 2015|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After the government signed an action plan with the United Nations, children were released from service and were no longer recruited. By 2014, Chad had been removed from the UN list of countries that use child soldiers in war.<ref name=":0" />

==== Côte d'Ivoire ====
During [[First Ivorian Civil War|Côte d’Ivoire’s civil war]] of 2002–2004, "children were recruited, often forcibly, by both sides",<ref name="CSUCS-1">[https://web.archive.org/web/20091226221427/http://www.child-soldiers.org/document/get?id=743 Child soldiers global report 2004: Africa Regional overview], [http://www.child-soldiers.org/contact/contact Child Soldiers International] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20070703045854/http://www.child-soldiers.org/contact/contact|date=3 July 2007}}.<!--Retrieved April 2009--></ref> and were also abducted by armed groups fighting the civil war in Liberia between 1999 and 2003.<ref name=":6" /> The ''Patriotic Youth –'' armed groups that included children in large numbers – received the active support of the government.<ref name=":6" /> Thousands of children saw membership of an armed group on either side of the war as a way to earn a living,<ref name=":8">{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/Handlers/Download.ashx?IDMF=26c0549d-aa35-4f1a-8e34-5956f8e2ec51|title=Child Soldiers Global Report 2008|last=Coalition to Stop the Use of Child Soldiers|first=|date=2008|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> although they were often unpaid, having to acquire money through extortion or begging.<ref name=":6" /> They were provided with automatic weapons, and girls were frequently abducted as sex slaves.<ref name=":6" />

Attempts to reach a peace agreement repeatedly failed, and although after 2006 children were gradually released from military groups, approximately 2,000 children remained.<ref name=":8" /> After President [[Laurent Gbagbo]] refused to recognise the 2010 election result, fighting flared up again and child recruitment increased.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.un.org/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=S/2013/245&Lang=E&Area=UNDOC|title=Report of the Secretary-General: Children and armed conflict (2013)|last=UN General Assembly|first=|date=2013|website=www.un.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> Under the new government, however, the UN brokered an Action Plan that included the release of all children and, in 2015, the UN reported that children were no longer recruited in the country.<ref name=":9">{{Cite web|url=http://www.un.org/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=S/2015/409&Lang=E&Area=UNDOC|title=Report of the Secretary-General: Children and armed conflict|last=UN General Assembly|first=|date=2015|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>

==== Eritrea ====
During its [[Eritrean War of Independence|30-year war for independence with Ethiopia]] (1961–1991) the [[Eritrean People's Liberation Front|Eritrean People’s Liberation Front]] was "widely acknowledged" to have used children extensively as soldiers, according to the Coalition to Stop the Use of Child Soldiers (now [[Child Soldiers International]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/shop/global-report-2001|title=Child Soldiers Global Report: 2001|last=Coalition to Stop the Use of Child Soldiers|first=|date=2001|website=|page=162|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180402040002/https://www.child-soldiers.org/shop/global-report-2001|archive-date=2 April 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=2018-05-24|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=":6" /> Once independence had been won, the Eritrean armed forces recruited and used children again during the [[Eritrean–Ethiopian War|two-year border war]] with Ethiopia in 1998.<ref name=":4" /> There were many reports of child recruitment and use (including conscription from age 15)<ref name=":6" />, but there is little information today about the extent of the practice, which is due in part to the absence of effective birth registration and age-verification system at the time.<ref name=":4" />

The UN reported in 2002 that children were no longer being used systematically by the Eritrean armed forces,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2002/03/30852-un-envoy-reports-no-evidence-child-soldiering-ethiopia-and-eritrea|title=UN envoy reports no evidence of ‘child soldiering’ in Ethiopia and Eritrea|last=|first=|date=2002-03-26|work=UN News|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708074728/https://news.un.org/en/story/2002/03/30852-un-envoy-reports-no-evidence-child-soldiering-ethiopia-and-eritrea|archive-date=8 July 2018|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the government acceded to the Optional Protocol on the involvement of children in armed conflict in 2005. Child recruitment continued, however; Human Rights Concern Eritrea reported in 2013 that all schoolchildren in 11<sup>th</sup> grade (approx. age 16) were made to spend the year at a military training camp, after which they were routinely recruited into the armed forces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hrc-eritrea.org/report-on-child-rights-violations-in-eritrea/|title=Report on Child Rights Violations in Eritrea|last=Human Rights Concern Eritrea|first=|date=19 November 2013|website=hrc-eritrea.org|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718154539/http://hrc-eritrea.org/report-on-child-rights-violations-in-eritrea/|archive-date=18 July 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=2018-05-24|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

==== Ethiopia ====
According to the [[Child Soldiers International|Coalition to Stop the Use of Child Soldiers]] in 2001 there were "credible reports" that the Ethiopian armed forces used thousands of children in its [[Eritrean–Ethiopian War|two-year border war]] with Eritrea between 1998 and 2000:<ref name=":12">{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/shop/global-report-2001|title=Child Soldiers Global Report: 2001|last=Coalition to Stop the Use of Child Soldiers|first=|date=2001|website=|page=165|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180402040002/https://www.child-soldiers.org/shop/global-report-2001|archive-date=2 April 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=2018-05-24|df=dmy-all}}</ref><blockquote>Testimonies of former child soldiers, NGOs and journalists provide evidence of child deployment on the [[Front line|front lines]] and in [[Human wave attack|massive waves]] across mine fields... Recruitment reportedly focused on Oromos and Somalis... and on grades 9 to 12 of secondary schools.<ref name=":12" /></blockquote>Children were also forcibly recruited in groups from public places.<ref name=":4" /> The lack of a functioning birth registration system has made it difficult to estimate the number of children affected, but it is clear that the use of children was widespread; for example, most Ethiopian prisoners of war in one large [[prisoner of war]] camp in Eritrea were estimated to be aged 14–18.<ref name=":4" />

The main opposition group in the 1990s, the [[Oromo Liberation Front]], also systematically recruited children, including by force.<ref name=":4" />

In 2008 it was reported that children were no longer used for military purposes in Ethiopia,<ref name=":8" /> and in 2014 the government ratified the Optional Protocol on the involvement of children in armed conflict.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://childsoldiersworldindex.org/view/ET|title=Child Soldiers World Index: Ethiopia|last=Child Soldiers International|first=|date=2017|website=childsoldiersworldindex.org|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525062600/http://childsoldiersworldindex.org/view/ET|archive-date=25 May 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=2018-05-24|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

==== Liberia ====
{{further|Second Liberian Civil War#Child soldiers}}
[[File:Liberian rebels (second civil war).png|thumb|Unidentified rebel fighters during the [[Second Liberian Civil War]], 1999–2003.]]
In Liberia’s civil wars (1989–1995, 1999–2003) all factions abducted children for direct combat, forced labour, and sexual slavery.<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":6" /> It was the common practice of commanders to give children drugs and threaten them with execution in order to enhance their obedience; for example, soldiers were frequently given [[Diazepam|valium]] before a battle, known as "bubbles" or "10-10".<ref name=":5">{{Cite news|url=http://www.lexisnexis.com/hottopics/lnacademic/?verb=sr&csi=5774&sr=HEADLINE(Boy+soldiers)%2BAND%2BDATE%2BIS%2B1995|title=Boy Soldiers|last=Frankel|first=Mark|date=14 August 1995|work=Newsweek|access-date=19 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220033458/http://www.lexisnexis.com/hottopics/lnacademic/?verb=sr&csi=5774&sr=HEADLINE(Boy+soldiers)%2BAND%2BDATE%2BIS%2B1995|archive-date=20 February 2018|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Children were often persuaded or forced to commit grave human rights violations against civilians, including rape, torture, and the abduction of other children for military use.<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":6" /> Children as young as 10 were used in direct combat.<ref name=":6" />

United Nations [[Rehabilitation and reintegration of child soldiers|disarmament, demobilisation and reintegration]] programs repeatedly failed when children quitted them, often to return to their former military unit, and after fighters rioted in protest at the absence of a financial reward for being disarmed.<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":6" /> A chronic lack of resources for reintegration also prompted child soldiers to enrol in other armed groups as a means of gainful employment.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Children and families affected by armed conflicts in Africa|last=Corbin|first=Joanne|publisher=NASW Press|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=39}}</ref> By 2004 more than 20,000 children needed to be demobilised and reunited with their communities.<ref name=":6" /> However, by October 2004 10,000 children had been released from their military units and were part of reintegration programs.<ref name=":6" /> 

By 2006 children were no longer being used by any military groups in the country, although armed groups from Côte d'Ivoire and Guinea continued to abduct Liberian children.<ref name=":8" /> {{As of|2018}}, children were no longer being used for military purposes in Liberia, and its armed forces were recruiting only adults over the age of 18.<ref name=":7">{{Cite web|url=http://childsoldiersworldindex.org/view/SL|title=Child Soldiers World Index: Sierra Leone|last=Child Soldiers International|first=|date=2018|website=childsoldiersworldindex.org|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517010103/http://childsoldiersworldindex.org/view/SL|archive-date=17 May 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=2018-05-16|df=dmy-all}}</ref> 

The use of child soldiers in Liberia was epitomised by The Small Boys Unit, established by Liberian President [[Charles Taylor (Liberian politician)|Charles Taylor]].<ref name=":5" /> The boys were not provided with sustenance, but were expected to engage in "snake patrol", looting surrounding villages.<ref name=":5" /> Taylor and others were later tried before the [[Special Court for Sierra Leone]] because of his involvement in recruiting child soldiers.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|title=Child Soldiers Global Report 2004|last=|first=|publisher=Coalition to Stop the Use of Child Soldiers|year=2004|isbn=|location=|pages=31-112}}</ref>

==== Rwanda ====
[[File:Nyanzale displaced persons camp children.jpg|thumb|Displaced children in the Democratic Republic of the Congo at risk of recruitment by Rwandese armed groups and local armed bandits.]]
An estimated 20,000 children took part in hostilities during the 1990s, including the 1994 [[Rwandan genocide|Rwanda genocide]] when many children were involved in committing atrocities.<ref name=":4" /> 5,000 children were in the national army,<ref name=":4" /> while others, including many street children, joined or were made to join armed groups.<ref name=":6" /> After the genocide, 4,500 children were detained on suspicion of participating in atrocities, and were incarcerated for several years without charge or trial;<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":8" /> some were sent to the Gitagata Re-Education Centre for males below 14 years of age.<ref name=":101">{{Cite web|url=https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/The%20Use%20of%20Children%20as%20Soldiers%20in%20Africa%20report.pdf|title=The Use of Children as Soldiers in Africa report|last=Jaffré|first=Françoise|date=21 January 2015|website=ReliefWeb|access-date=18 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220092236/https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/The%20Use%20of%20Children%20as%20Soldiers%20in%20Africa%20report.pdf|archive-date=20 February 2018|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the late 1990s, children were widely recruited again, often by force, to fight in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).<ref name="CSUCS-12">[https://web.archive.org/web/20091226221427/http://www.child-soldiers.org/document/get?id=743 Child soldiers global report 2004: Africa Regional overview], [http://www.child-soldiers.org/contact/contact Child Soldiers International] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20070703045854/http://www.child-soldiers.org/contact/contact|date=3 July 2007}}.<!--Retrieved April 2009--></ref>

Initial demobilisation and reintegration programmes failed after many schools banned former child soldiers<ref name=":4" /> and a high rate of unemployment rendered them vulnerable to re-recruitment by militia groups.<ref name=":6" /> In 2003, as the Rwandan military presence in the DRC reduced, so did the demand for child soldiers.<ref name=":6" /> The government introduced new legislation to raise the minimum enlistment age 18 and the armed forces stopped recruiting children.<ref name=":6" /> Nonetheless, armed groups continued to do so, albeit to a reduced extent, for their operations in the DRC.<ref name=":9" />

====Sierra Leone====
{{Main|Child soldiers in Sierra Leone}}
During the [[Sierra Leone Civil War]] (1991–2002) thousands of children were recruited by government armed forces and non-government armed groups, particularly the anti-government [[Revolutionary United Front]] (RUF) and the [[Armed Forces Revolutionary Council]] (AFRC), and the pro-government [[Civil Defence Forces]] (CDF).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2012/04/11/armed-conflict-sierra-leone|title=The Armed Conflict in Sierra Leone|last=Human Rights Watch|first=|date=2012-04-11|work=|access-date=2018-05-16|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022164329/https://www.hrw.org/news/2012/04/11/armed-conflict-sierra-leone|archive-date=22 October 2017|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

Children were often forcibly recruited, given drugs and used to commit atrocities.<ref name=":4" /> Thousands of girls were also recruited as soldiers and often subjected to sexual exploitation. Many of the children were survivors of attacks on villages, which were routinely ordered to hand over their children to armed groups.<ref name=":4" /> By 2001, an estimated 10,000 children were being used for military purposes by government armed forces and various armed groups, particularly the RUF.<ref name=":4" />

After 2002, when the war was declared over, an extensive United Nations [[Rehabilitation and reintegration of child soldiers|disarmament, demobilisation and reintegration]] programme reunited most former child soldiers with their communities, although it drew criticism for neglecting the needs of women and girls.<ref name=":6" />

In June 2007 the [[Special Court for Sierra Leone]] found three men from the rebel Armed Forces Revolutionary Council (AFRC) guilty of war crimes, crimes against humanity, and other serious violations of international humanitarian law, including the recruitment of children under the age of 15 years into the armed forces. With this the Special Court became the first ever UN-backed tribunal to secure a conviction for the military conscription of children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sc-sl.org/Press/pressrelease-062007.pdf|title="Guilty Verdicts in the Trial of the AFRC Accused"|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029201800/http://www.sc-sl.org/Press/pressrelease-062007.pdf|archivedate=29 October 2008|deadurl=yes|df=}}&nbsp;{{small|(104&nbsp;KB)}}, press release from the Special Court for Sierra Leone, 20 June 2007; [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/20/AR2007062000952.html?hpid=moreheadlines "Sierra Leone Convicts 3 of War Crimes"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003183441/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/20/AR2007062000952.html?hpid=moreheadlines |date=3 October 2018 }}, ''[[Associated Press]]'', 20 June 2007 (hosted by ''[[The Washington Post]]''); {{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6221112.stm|title=First S Leone war crimes verdicts|date=20 June 2007|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=21 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122151146/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6221112.stm|archive-date=22 November 2015|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> 

{{As of|2018}}, children were no longer being used for military purposes in Sierra Leone, and its armed forces were recruiting only adults over the age of 18.<ref name=":7" />

In his book ''[[A Long Way Gone|A Long Way Gone: Memoirs of a Child Soldier]]'', [[Ishmael Beah]] chronicles his life during the conflict in Sierra Leone.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/69423270|title=A long way gone : memoirs of a boy soldier|last=Beah|first=Ishmael|date=|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|year=2007|isbn=0374105235|edition=|location=New York|pages=|oclc=69423270|access-date=16 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090908175218/http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/69423270|archive-date=8 September 2009|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In ''Armies of the Young: Child Soldiers in War and Terrorism'' anthropologist [[David M. Rosen]] discusses the murders, rapes, tortures, and thousands of amputations committed by the RUF [[Small Boys Unit]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/anthropological_quarterly/v079/79.2glazer.html|title=Project MUSE|publisher=Muse.jhu.edu|doi=10.1353/anq.2006.0021|accessdate=12 May 2012}}</ref> The film ''[[Blood Diamond]]'' is set during the civil war.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0450259/plotsummary?ref_=tt_stry_pl|title=Blood Diamond|last=IMDB|first=|date=2006|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322210643/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0450259/plotsummary?ref_=tt_stry_pl|archive-date=22 March 2015|dead-url=no|access-date=2018-03-22|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The issue is also explored in the ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'' episode, [[Bones (season 8)|''The Survivor In The Soap'']].<ref>{{Citation|title="Bones" The Survivor in the Soap (TV Episode 2013)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2661372/plotsummary|accessdate=2018-05-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160520184042/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt2661372/plotsummary|archive-date=20 May 2016|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

====Uganda====
[[File:David LIvingstone speaks to participants about his experiences as a child soldier with the LRA in Uganda. (24500877565).jpg|thumb|David Livingstone speaks about his experiences as a child soldier with the [[Lord's Resistance Army]] in Uganda.]]
Over a period of twenty years the rebel [[Lord's Resistance Army]] (LRA) has abducted more than 30,000 boys and girls as soldiers or sex slaves.<ref name=":48">{{cite web|url=http://womennewsnetwork.net/2009/01/13/ugandagirlsoldier809/|title=Girl Soldiers – The cost of survival in Northern Uganda, Women News Network – WNN|date=13 January 2009|publisher=Womennewsnetwork.net|accessdate=12 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523212431/http://womennewsnetwork.net/2009/01/13/ugandagirlsoldier809/|archive-date=23 May 2012|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Joseph Kony]] began the Lord's Resistance Army (LRA) in 1987, originally to protect northern Ugandans from the 1986 military coup by the People's National Resistance Army,. Stating that he "received messages from God" Kony began attacking his own people, the [[Acholi people|Acholi]], to establish a new theocratic government in Uganda based on the principles of the "Ten Commandments of God". This attempt by the LRA to gain control of the Ugandan government via roaming armies used boy- as well as girl-children as soldiers,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://womennewsnetwork.net/2009/01/13/ugandagirlsoldier809/|title=Girl Soldiers – The cost of survival in Northern Uganda|publisher=|accessdate=2 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006094239/http://womennewsnetwork.net/2009/01/13/ugandagirlsoldier809/|archive-date=6 October 2014|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> such as [[Grace Akallo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hereandnow.wbur.org/2012/04/19/kony-child-soldier|title=Former Kony Child Soldier Tells Her Story|date=19 April 2012|work=[[WBUR]]|accessdate=2 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209232158/http://hereandnow.wbur.org/2012/04/19/kony-child-soldier|archive-date=9 February 2014|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

The LRA expansion into South Sudan, the Central African Republic and the Democratic Republic of Congo has used large numbers of children as active combatants and participants in extreme violence. On the 21{{nbsp}}October 2008 an appeal by the UN Security Council was made asking for the LRA to cease all military action in the DRC immediately.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.securitycouncilreport.org/atf/cf/%7B65BFCF9B-6D27-4E9C-8CD3-CF6E4FF96FF9%7D/Uganda%20SPRST%202008%2038.pdf|title=UN Security Council Statement Oct 21, 2008|format=PDF|accessdate=12 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226070838/http://www.securitycouncilreport.org/atf/cf/%7B65BFCF9B-6D27-4E9C-8CD3-CF6E4FF96FF9%7D/Uganda%20SPRST%202008%2038.pdf|archive-date=26 February 2012|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 14{{nbsp}}June 2002 Uganda deposited its instrument of ratification of the [[Rome Statute]], and on 16{{nbsp}}December 2003 the Government of Uganda referred the situation concerning northern Uganda to the prosecutor of the International Criminal Court (ICC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icc-cpi.int/library/cases/ICC_20051410-056-1_English.pdf|title=The situation in Uganda Basic Information No.: ICC20051410.056.1-E, The Hague, 14 October 2005|publisher=Icc-cpi.int|format=PDf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010074543/http://www.icc-cpi.int/library/cases/ICC_20051410-056-1_English.pdf|archivedate=10 October 2007|deadurl=yes}}</ref> The ICC investigated the situation<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icc-cpi.int/library/organs/otp/speeches/LMO_20051014_English.pdf|title=Statement by Luis Moreno-Ocampo, Prosecutor of the International Criminal Court, The Hague, 14 October 2005|format=PDF|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051117064423/http://www.icc-cpi.int/library/organs/otp/speeches/LMO_20051014_English.pdf|archivedate=17 November 2005|deadurl=yes}}</ref> and on 14{{nbsp}}October 2005 issued indictments against Lord's Resistance Army leader Joseph Kony and four other commanders for [[War crime|war crimes]]: Vincent Otti; Raska Lukwiya (indictment terminated, deceased); Okot Odhiambo; and [[Dominic Ongwen]]. The warrant for Kony, Otti and Odhiambo includes the alleged crime of the forced enlisting of children contrary to the Rome Statute Art. 8(2) (e)(vii).<ref>Yasmin Anwar [http://berkeley.edu/news/media/releases/2007/06/15_LRA.shtml Damning report on Uganda war crimes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080629083426/http://www.berkeley.edu/news/media/releases/2007/06/15_LRA.shtml |date=29 June 2008 }}, [http://www.berkeley.edu/misc/newscenter-feedback.shtml UC Berkeley NewsCenter] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104171414/http://www.berkeley.edu/misc/newscenter-feedback.shtml |date=4 January 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icc-cpi.int/press/pressreleases/114.html|title=Warrant of Arrest unsealed against five LRA Commanders|author=ICC Prosecutor|date=14 October 2005|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070423052817/http://www.icc-cpi.int/press/pressreleases/114.html|archivedate=23 April 2007|deadurl=yes}}</ref>

The National Resistance Army also made use of child soldiers.<ref name="green47">{{cite book|title=The Wizard of the Nile: The Hunt for Africa's Most Wanted|last=Green|first=Matthew|publisher=Portobello Books|year=2008|isbn=978-1-84627-031-4|page=47|authorlink=Matthew Green (journalist)}}</ref> Between 2003 and 2007, non-state armed groups fighting the LRA also used children.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web|url=http://childsoldiersworldindex.org/view/UG|title=Child Soldiers World Index: Uganda|last=Child Soldiers International|first=|date=2018|website=childsoldiersworldindex.org|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330012949/http://childsoldiersworldindex.org/view/UG|archive-date=30 March 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=2018-03-29|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

In 2007 the Ugandan government agreed an action plan with the UN to end the use of child soldiers and in 2008 the country no longer appeared on the UN list of countries that recruit and use children.<ref name=":3" />

=== Americas ===

==== El Salvador ====
[[File:ERP combatants Perquín 1990 35.jpg|thumb|right|Rebel Salvadoran soldier boy combatant in Perquin, El Salvador 1990, during the Salvadoran Civil War.]]
During the [[Salvadoran Civil War|civil war between 1980 and 1992]] the Salvadoran military and the main opposition group, the ''[[Frente Farabundo Martí de Liberación Nacional|Frente Farabundo Martí de Liberación National]]'' (FMLN)'','' recruited children extensively. The recruitment was frequently carried out by force and focused on economically suppressed regions.<ref name=":4" /> A fifth of the army’s personnel were aged under 18, as were a quarter of the FMLN.<ref name=":11">{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/shop/experiences-and-psychocial-impact-of-the-el-salvador-civil-war-on-child-soldiers|title=Experiences and psychocial impact of the El Salvador civil war on child soldiers|last=Santacruz|first=Maria|last2=Arana|first2=Rubi|date=2002|website=Child Soldiers International|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522043014/https://www.child-soldiers.org/shop/experiences-and-psychocial-impact-of-the-el-salvador-civil-war-on-child-soldiers|archive-date=22 May 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=2018-05-21|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a group of 278 former FMLN child soldiers interviewed for a study, the average age of recruitment was 10 years.<ref name=":11" /> The large majority of child recruits on both sides were living in poverty, and had been largely deprived of formal education.<ref name=":11" /> Many children who were not recruited by force joined of their own volition, mainly either to improve their circumstances or because they believed in the cause.<ref name=":11" /> 

After the civil war came to a close, [[Rehabilitation and reintegration of child soldiers|rehabilitation and reintegration programmes]] for children mostly failed; the majority of FMLN children were not involved in them, and the large majority of those who were dropped out of them.<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":11" /> A decade after the peace accord former child soldiers were still experiencing nightmares, depression, anxiety, and related signs of psychiatric trauma.<ref name=":11" /> 

Today, the Salvadoran military no longer sends children to war, but it still recruits and trains them from the age of 16.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://childsoldiersworldindex.org/view/SV|title=Child Soldiers World Index: El Salvador|last=Child Soldiers International|first=|date=2017|website=childsoldiersworldindex.org|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522042153/http://childsoldiersworldindex.org/view/SV|archive-date=22 May 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=2018-05-21|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

=== Middle East ===

====Iran====
[[File:Detail of Revolutionary Mural Showing Child Soldier from Iran-Iraq War - Ardabil - Iranian Azerbaijan - Iran (7421107610).jpg|thumb|Detail of a propaganda mural chowing a child soldier from the [[Iran–Iraq War|Iran-Iraq War]], in Ardabil, Iranian Azerbaijan.]]
During the [[Iran–Iraq War]] (1980–1988) the armed forces used children widely; the extent of the practice is not known but the number of children involved is thought to be in the tens of thousands.<ref name=":4" /> Armed groups associated with the government advertised widely for children from age 14 to join them, and the country's Supreme Leader, [[Ruhollah Khomeini|Ayatollah Khomeini]], urged children to fight at the front.<ref name=":4" /> According to the Coalition to Stop the Use of Child Soldiers (now [[Child Soldiers International]]):<blockquote>Ayatollah Khomeini declared that parental permission was unnecessary for those going to the front, that volunteering for military duty was a religious obligation, and that serving in the armed forces took priority over all other forms of work or study. Various sources reported that children were indoctrinated into participating in combat. They were given "keys to paradise" and promised that they would go directly to heaven if they died as [[Martyr|martyrs]] against the Iraqi enemy.<ref name=":4" /></blockquote>The children involved were overwhelmingly from slums and poor villages,<ref name=":4" /> and some participated without the knowledge of their parents, including [[Mohammad Hossein Fahmideh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041216144735/http://www.iran-daily.com/1383/2129/html/panorama.htm|title=Iran Daily|date=2004-12-16|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> Thousands of children took part in [[Human wave attack|human wave]] attacks, leading to widespread deaths and injuries.<ref name=":4" /><ref name="unicef-1996">{{cite web|url=http://www.unicef.org/sowc96/2csoldrs.htm|title=The State of the World's Children 1996|website=UNICEF|access-date=28 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208163922/https://www.unicef.org/sowc96/2csoldrs.htm|archive-date=8 February 2018|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="child-labor-global-view">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6JznQqlZmHkC&pg=PA120&lpg=PA120&dq=iran+child+soldiers#v=onepage&q=iran%20child%20soldiers&f=false|title=Child Labor: A Global View|date=2004|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=0313322775|editor1-last=Schmitz|editor1-first=Cathryne L.|page=120|editor2-last=Traver|editor2-first=Elizabeth KimJin|editor3-last=Larson|editor3-first=Desi}}</ref> The total number of all Iranian casualties is estimated to be 200,000–600,000,<ref name="hiro205">{{cite book|title=The Longest War: The Iran–Iraq Military Conflict|last=Hiro|first=Dilip|publisher=Routledge|year=1991|isbn=9780415904063|location=New York|page=205|oclc=22347651|authorlink=Dilip Hiro}}</ref><ref name="Rajaee1997">{{cite book|title=Iranian Perspectives on the Iran-Iraq War|last=Rajaee|first=Farhang|publisher=University Press of Florida|year=1997|isbn=9780813014760|location=Gainesville|page=2|oclc=492125659}}</ref><ref name="Mikaberidze2011">{{cite book|title=Conflict and Conquest in the Islamic World: A Historical Encyclopedia|last=Mikaberidze|first=Alexander|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2011|isbn=9781598843361|location=Santa Barbara, California|page=418|oclc=775759780}}</ref><ref>Hammond Atlas of the 20th Century (1999) P. 134-5</ref><ref name="Dunnigan 1991">Dunnigan, A Quick and Dirty Guide to War (1991)</ref><ref name="Twentieth Century World History 1997">Dictionary of Twentieth Century World History, by Jan Palmowski (Oxford, 1997)</ref><ref name="ReferenceA">Clodfelter, Michael, Warfare and Armed Conflict: A Statistical Reference to Casualty and Other Figures, 1618–1991</ref><ref name="Chirot, Daniel 1994">Chirot, Daniel: ''Modern Tyrants: The Power and Prevalence of Evil in Our Age'' (1994)</ref><ref>"B&J": Jacob Bercovitch and Richard Jackson, ''International Conflict: A Chronological Encyclopedia of Conflicts and Their Management 1945–1995'' (1997) p. 195</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2oGSb23T5F8&t=51m19s|title=Christopher Hitchens – Whisky, Cigarettes and Jefferson [2006]|publisher=YouTube|access-date=28 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313034220/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2oGSb23T5F8&t=51m19s|archive-date=13 March 2016|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> of which approximately a third were aged 15–19 (and 3 percent under 14), according to one assessment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kurzman.unc.edu/death-tolls-of-the-iran-iraq-war/|title=Death Tolls of the Iran-Iraq War|last1=Kurzman|first1=Charles|website=kurzman.unc.edu/|access-date=28 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321154456/http://kurzman.unc.edu/death-tolls-of-the-iran-iraq-war/|archive-date=21 March 2018|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

After the war, the ''[[Basij]],'' an official militia organisation, continued to recruit children from age 15, focusing on those living in poverty and sometimes recruiting them by force.<ref name=":6" /> In 2004, the ''Basij'' was estimated to have as many as a million members of all ages. ''[[Ansar-e Hezbollah|Ansar-e Hizbollah]]'', an armed group tolerated by the government, also recruited children widely in the 2000s, with no age restriction.<ref name=":6" /> {{As of|2018}}, the Iranian armed forces continue to enlist from age 16 and the government has not yet ratified the [[Optional Protocol on the Involvement of Children in Armed Conflict|Optional Protocol on the involvement of children in armed conflict]].

==== Iraq ====
The government of [[Saddam Hussein]] maintained 'boot camps' of civilian youths between the ages of 12 and 17 that involved small arms training and [[Ba'athist#The Iraq-based Ba'ath Party|Ba'athist]] political indoctrination. [[Iraqi anti-Saddam Hussein groups|Iraqi opposition]] sources and the US State Department reported that children who refused faced punishment. The state incorporated children as young as ten into the ''[[Futuwwa#Modern reuse of the name|Futuwah]]'' and ''[[Ashbal Saddam]]'' youth movements and then subjected them to military training, sometimes for 14 hours a day.<ref name="2001-Iraq">{{cite web|url=http://www.refworld.org/docid/498805f0c.html|title=Child Soldiers Global Report 2001 – Iraq|last=Child Soldiers International|first=|date=2001|website=|publisher=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920074539/http://www.refworld.org/docid/498805f0c.html|archive-date=20 September 2013|dead-url=no|accessdate=4 August 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> P. W. Singer has compared the groups to the ''Hitler Jugend''.<ref name="saddam">{{cite web|url=http://www.brookings.edu/papers/2003/0114iraq_singer.aspx|title=Facing Saddam's Child Soldiers|author=[[P. W. Singer]]|date=14 January 2003|publisher=[[Brookings Institution]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212100221/http://www.brookings.edu/papers/2003/0114iraq_singer.aspx|archivedate=12 February 2010|deadurl=yes|accessdate=3 August 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the [[Gulf War]] 12-year-old boys fought for the Iraqis. Children also participated in the [[Iran–Iraq War]].<ref name="2001-Iraq" />

In the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], US forces fought children at Nasariya, Karbala, and Kirkuk, and the US sent captured child combatants to [[Abu Ghraib prison]].<ref name="aft">{{Cite news|url=http://www.aft.org/pubs-reports/american_educator/issues/winter05-06/singer.htm|title=Child Soldiers|author=[[P. W. Singer]]|date=Winter 2005–2006|work=[[American Educator]]|accessdate=4 August 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081129115512/http://www.aft.org/pubs-reports/american_educator/issues/winter05-06/singer.htm|archivedate=29 November 2008|deadurl=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2009 a UN report on the post-war Iraqi occupation stated that the [[Iraqi insurgency (Iraq War)|Iraqi insurgency]] had used children as combatants; it noted, for example, a suicide attack against Kirkuk's police commander by a boy aged between 10 and 13.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/meast/01/18/iraq.rights/index.html|title=U.N. reports children used as combatants in Iraq|date=19 January 2006|accessdate=3 August 2009|publisher=[[CNN.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213060509/http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/meast/01/18/iraq.rights/index.html|archive-date=13 February 2009|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> 

=== Asia ===

====  Cambodia ====
[[File:Khmer Rouge.JPG|thumb|Child dressed as ''[[Khmer Rouge]]'' soldier.]]
In the 1970s the ''[[Khmer Rouge]]'' exploited thousands of desensitised, conscripted children in their early teens to commit mass murder and other atrocities during the [[Cambodian Civil War|Cambodian civil war]] and [[Cambodian genocide|subsequent genocide]].<ref name=":10">{{cite web|url=http://www.rfa.org/english/features/blogs/cambodiablog/blog6_cambodia_southerland-20060720.html|title=Cambodia Diary 6: Child Soldiers — Driven by Fear and Hate|last=Southerland|first=D|date=2006-07-20|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320105641/https://www.rfa.org/english/features/blogs/cambodiablog/blog6_cambodia_southerland-20060720.html|archive-date=20 March 2018|dead-url=no|accessdate=2018-03-28|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The indoctrinated children were taught to follow any order without hesitation.<ref name=":10" /> After it was deposed in 1979, the ''Khmer Rouge'' fought a [[Guerrilla warfare|guerrilla war]] against the new government, and until at least 1998 relied heavily on child recruits, including forced recruitment by abduction.<ref name=":4" /> During this period, the children were deployed mainly in unpaid support roles, such as ammunition-carriers, and also as combatants.<ref name=":4" />

Cambodia's state armed forces also recruited children widely. Throughout the 1990s the army was recruiting children from the age of 10 and using them in armed conflict, mainly as porters and spies, and also as combatants.<ref name=":4" /> Four percent of the army were children, according to an estimate in the ''[[The Cambodia Daily|Cambodia Daily]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/Handlers/Download.ashx?IDMF=adc88bff-1916-4317-b184-d9079e7b0bb8|title=Cambodia Daily|last=|first=|date=2001|work=Cambodia Daily|access-date=2018-05-21|via=Coalition to Stop the Use of Child Soldiers: 'Child Soldiers Global Report: 2001'}}</ref> Many children had fled the ''Khmer Rouge'' without a means to feed themselves and hoped that joining the government forces would enable them to survive, although local commanders frequently denied them any pay.<ref name=":4" /> Children often capitalised on the lack of an effective birth registration system to lie about their age in order to enlist.<ref name=":4" /> Other children, some as young as 8, were forced to join.<ref name=":4" />

By 2000, the Cambodian government had signed the [[Optional Protocol on the Involvement of Children in Armed Conflict]] and its armed forces resolved to recruit adults only.<ref name=":4" /> Meanwhile, the ''Khmer Rouge'' had collapsed with the death of its leader, [[Pol Pot]], in 1998.<ref name=":4" /> By 2004, children were no longer being recruited in the country, although the [[Rehabilitation and reintegration of child soldiers|demobilisation programmes]] were inadequate, according to [[UNICEF]], failing to offer appropriate rehabilitative support to released children.<ref name=":6" />

==== Sri Lanka ====
{{Main|Use of child soldiers in Sri Lanka}}
[[File:Sri lanka enfants soldats.jpg|thumb|Former child soldiers at a centre for rehabilitation and reintegration into their communities, Sri Lanka.]]
Between 1983 and 2009 Sri Lanka’s government fought a civil war with the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]] (Tamil Tigers). For its entire duration the Tamil Tigers and other armed groups made routine use of child recruits, typically aged 14–17 and sometimes under 10.<ref name=":4" /><ref name="ZN">Bureau Report ''[http://www.zeenews.com/znnew/articles.asp?aid=331811&sid=SAS LTTE rebels make child recruitment illegal: Report] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930205926/http://www.zeenews.com/znnew/articles.asp?aid=331811&sid=SAS |date=30 September 2007 }}'', [[Zee News]] 27 October 2006</ref> Some children enlisted to escape deprivation or racism, or during compulsory military training at their school when they were exposed to recruitment propaganda.<ref name=":4" /> Others were recruited by force when walking home from school or after the Tigers pressurised families to surrender one child, as per its policy.<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":6" /> In 2001, international sources estimated that 40 percent of Tamil Tiger personnel were children, contrary to official statements insisting that the organisation did not use them.<ref name=":4" /> Sri Lankan soldiers nicknamed one unit the "Baby Battalion", due to the number of children in it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928090515/http://www.lankaeverything.com/printnews.php?pid=20060918001845.php|title=Sri Lanka Tamil Tigers abduct teens to fight|last=LankaEverything.com|first=|date=2006-09-18|website=web.archive.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> Although state armed forces recruited only adults over the age of 18, they supported the [[Karuna group]], a Tamil splinter organisation opposed to the Tamil Tigers, to recruit children by force.<ref name=":8" /> The government also used detained Tamil Tiger children for propaganda by exposing them to the media.<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":8" />

The first international initiative to demobilise and reintegrate children into their communities began in 2003, but was halted in 2004 because the Tigers failed to keep their commitment to release children from their ranks.<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":6" /> The organisation began to release children in 2004, but continued to enlist several thousand, albeit in progressively smaller numbers, until at least 2007.<ref name=":8" /> The Tamil Tigers were defeated in 2009 and all other parties to the conflict stopped recruiting children in the same year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.un.org/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=S/2011/250&Lang=E&Area=UNDOC|title=Children and Armed Conflict: Annual Report of the Secretary-General, 2011|last=UN General Assembly|first=|date=2011|website=www.un.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180518200355/http://www.un.org/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=S%2F2011%2F250&Lang=E&Area=UNDOC|archive-date=18 May 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=2018-05-25|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

=== Europe ===

==== Chechnya/Russia ====
During the [[First Chechen War]], Chechen separatist forces included a large number of boys and girls, some as young as 11. According to the UN: "Child soldiers in Chechnya were reportedly assigned the same tasks as adult combatants, and served on the front lines soon after joining the armed forces."<ref name=":38">{{cite web|url=http://www1.umn.edu/humanrts/commission/country52/1996_13.htm|title=UN Commission on Human Rights – The situation of human rights in the Republic of Chechnya of the Russian Federation (Mar 96)|publisher=.umn.edu|accessdate=12 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211102551/http://www1.umn.edu/humanrts/commission/country52/1996_13.htm|archive-date=11 February 2012|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2004 under-18s were still believed to be involved in a range of armed groups in the war against Russia; some allegedly took part in suicide bombings.<ref name="CSGR2004-217">{{cite web|url=http://www.child-soldiers.org/document_get.php?id=966|title=Child Soldiers Global Report 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041217103244/http://www.child-soldiers.org/document_get.php?id=966|archive-date=2004-12-17|dead-url=yes}}&nbsp;{{small|(2.29&nbsp;MB)}} [[Child Soldiers International]] p. 217</ref>

====United Kingdom====
Children aged 17 were sent to the [[Falklands War]] in 1982 (where three were killed) and the [[Gulf War]] in 1990–91 (where two were killed).<ref name=":4" /> 17-year-olds were also deployed as [[NATO]] peacekeepers in the former Yugoslavia during the 1990s.<ref name=":4" /> Having initially resisted international negotiations to prevent the deployment of children,<ref name=":02">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/837635842|title=Campaigning for justice: Human rights advocacy in practice|last=Becker|first=J|date=|publisher=Stanford University Press|year=2013|isbn=9780804774512|location=Stanford, California|pages=11–31|chapter=Campaigning to stop the use of child soldiers|oclc=837635842}}</ref> the UK agreed to deploy adults only when it signed the [[Optional Protocol on the Involvement of Children in Armed Conflict]] in 2000, but remained committed to recruiting and training children from age 16.<ref name=":4" /> Between 2003 and 2010 22 personnel aged 17 were sent to Afghanistan and Iraq, reportedly in error.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/shop/letter-from-uk-minister-of-defence-regarding-deployment-of-under-18s-on-combat-operations-1|title=Letter from UK Minister of Defence regarding deployment of under-18s on combat operations|last=Child Soldiers International|first=|date=|website=Child Soldiers International|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418101630/https://www.child-soldiers.org/shop/letter-from-uk-minister-of-defence-regarding-deployment-of-under-18s-on-combat-operations-1|archive-date=18 April 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=2018-02-05|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

During the [[The Troubles|Troubles]] in Northern Ireland (c. 1960s to 1998) it was common for paramilitary groups to recruit and use children, including as combatants.<ref name=":27">{{Cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/issues/violence/cts/smyth1.htm|title=Half the Battle: Understanding the impact of 'the Troubles' on children and young people (Chapter 3: Deaths of children and young people in the Troubles)|last=Smyth|first=M|date=|website=cain.ulst.ac.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105081728/http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/issues/violence/cts/smyth1.htm|archive-date=5 November 2014|dead-url=no|access-date=2018-02-13|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://irishpeaceprocess.blog/2018/01/10/ira-war-crimes-enlisting-children/|title=IRA War Crimes – Enlisting Children|last=O'Doherty|first=S|date=2018-01-10|work=The Irish Peace Process|access-date=2018-02-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313032203/https://irishpeaceprocess.blog/2018/01/10/ira-war-crimes-enlisting-children/|archive-date=13 March 2018|dead-url=no|language=en-US|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Five children in Republican [[Paramilitary|paramilitary groups]], seven in Loyalist paramilitary groups, and five in the [[British Armed Forces|British armed forces]], died during the conflict.<ref name=":27" /> The youngest, Cathleen McCartland, was recruited by the [[Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) and was aged 12 when she was killed in Belfast.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/troubles-the-children-killed-in-line-of-fire-in-northern-ireland-31136428.html|title=Troubles: The children killed in line of fire in Northern Ireland|last=Cusack|first=J|date=2015-04-13|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2018-02-13|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|last2=Browne|first2=M|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>

